Already, we have started the year on a false start. As the students reported back to school, Education Cabinet Secretary Prof George Magoha urged teachers to be innovative and let students learn under trees as a solution to congestion in classrooms. This would have been funny had we not been talking about the lives and the future of our children. It is like telling a person without clothes to be innovative enough and walk naked.
Teaching under trees
Rwanda has constructed over 20,000 schools and when Prof Magoha was asked about that, he said that we should not compare ourselves to a smaller country whose population is like that of one region in Kenya. One would have thought that our bigger population is a resource that can help us do more. The irony is that those who tell our teachers to be innovative enough and teach children under trees always take their children to international schools and abroad. Maybe that explains ‘their disconnect’ with the suffering of the ordinary citizens.
We must think of innovative solutions. Instead of children learning under trees, we can have the military, the National Youth Service and community volunteers help put up temporary classrooms for the kids. That would be cheaper and would guarantee them some relative comfort as they learn.



